ds.definition: Characterizing the ovum when it has two primary germinallayers.
To delineate. [Obs.]These two stones as they are here defigured. Weever.
Of or pertaining to Lombardy, or the inhabitants of Lombardy.
The religious tenets or practices of the Bahais.
See Femerell.
A petty or powerless king. [R.]there were at this time two other royalets, as only kings by hisleave. Fuller.
Adorned with trophies.The trophied arches, storied halls, invade. Pope.
See Sequin.
A mechanic whose occupation is to build mills, or to set uptheir machinery.
An instrument for determining the sensibility of the platesemployed in photographic processes to luminous rays.
The metal tungsten. [Obs.]
Deeply pitted, like a honeycomb.

The only existing genus of Merostomata. It includes only a fewspecies from the East Indies, and one (Limulus polyphemus) from theAtlantic coast of North America. Called also Molucca crab, king crab,horseshoe crab, and horsefoot.

A fern of the genus Osmunda, or flowering fern. The mostremarkable species is the osmund royal, or royal fern (Osmundaregalis), which grows in wet or boggy places, and has large bipinnatefronds, often with a panicle of capsules at the top. The rootstockcontains much starch, and has been used in stiffening linen.
See Poteen.
To run or pass under; especially (Naut.), to pass along andunder, as a cable, for the purpose of taking it in, or of examiningit.
Fit to be applied as a plaster; glutinous; adhesive; as,emplastic applications.
The department of musical science which treats of the length ofsounds.
A group of Isectivora, including the colugo.
Not bloody. Dryden. Unbloody sacrifice. (a) A sacrifice inwhich no victim is slain. (b) (R. C. Ch.) The Mass.
A form of monochasium in which the lateral branches arisealternately on opposite sides of the false axis; -- called alsoscorpioid cyme. --Cin*cin"nal (#), a.
The quality or state of being indocile; dullness of intellect;unteachableness; intractableness.The stiffness and indocility of the Pharisees. W. Montagu.
An extensive order of bony fishes including most of the commonmarket species, as bass, salmon, cod, perch, etc.
A thicket of canes. Ellicott.
Pertaining to, or designating, a nitrogenous acid obtained as ayellow crystalline substance by the oxidation of quinine.
Pertaining to, or derived from, castor oil; formerly,designating an acid now called ricinoleic acid.
Of or pertaining to the earth. [R.]
The quality or state of being other or different; alterity;oppositeness.
A small bundle or collection; a compact cluster; as, a fascicleof fibers; a fascicle of flowers or roots.
Renewed enjoiment.
One of the Longirostres.
To utter as a rhapsody, or in the manner of a rhapsody Sterne.
See under Violet.
Having a truncheon.
imp. of Undergo.
With quick beating or palpitation; pitapat. Congreve.
That part of the breast of an animal which extends from thefore legs back beneath the ribs; also applied to the fore part of ahorse, from the shoulders to the bottom of the chest.
One of a group of nitrogenous phosphorized principles, supposedby Thudichum to exist in brain tissue.
According to measure or proportion; proportionable;proportionate. [Obs.]

A tall perennial grass (Sorghum Halepense), valuable in theSouthern and Western States for pasture and hay. The rootstocks arelarge and juicy and are eagerly sought by swine. Called also Cubagrass, Means grass, Evergreen millet, and Arabian millet.
A made-up face; a grimace. "What mops and mowes it makes!"Beau. & Fl.
Of or pertaining to compotations and merrymaking; happeningwhere company is drinking together; as, symposiac meetings.Symposiac disputations amongst my acquaintance. Arbuthnot.
A genus of thin papery bright green seaweeds including thekinds called sea lettuce.

A suffix to names of persons or places, used to denote acollection of notable sayings, literary gossip, anecdotes, etc. Thus,Scaligerana is a book containing the sayings of Scaliger, Johnsonianaof Johnson, etc.
Following the practice of Pharisees; Pharisaic. [Obs.]"Pharisean disciples." Milton.
Putridity. Floyer.
Same as Tousle. [Colloq.]
A plane figure having four sides and angles; a quadrangle, as asquare, a rhombus, etc.
The long-tailed duck. See Old Squaw.
See under Intercolumniation. -n.
The trunk or stem of a tree, or that which is like it.Enormous elm-tree boles did stoop and lean. Tennyson.
Prolonged at the base, as certain leaves.
The art of employment of an historiographer.
In a running or hasty manner; carelessly.
A writer of glosses or of a glossary; a commentator; ascholiast. Tyrwhitt.
One of a sect of ancient Christians, who, in supposed imitationof the first believers, renounced all their possessions.
Woody. [Obs.] Skelton.
See Sequin.
To sprinkle with, or as with, stars; to decorate with, or aswith, stars; to bestud. "Bestarred with anemones." W. Black.
One who caricatures.
The Angora goat. See Angora goat, under Angora.
Opinionated. [Obs.]
A suborder of Theromorpha, including terrestrial reptiles fromthe Permian formation.
Petty theft. [Scot.] Holinshed.
Hard; inflexible; obstinate; sour in aspect; hardy; bold.[Scot.]A dour wife, a sour old carlin. C. Reade.
A genus of plants, one species of which (A. Mexicanum) haslavender-blue flowers in dense clusters.

"A wooden pin stuck anciently on the sides of the bedstead, tohold the clothes from slipping on either side." Johnson.Hostess, accommodate us with a bedstaff. B. Jonson.Say there is no virtue in cudgels and bedstaves. Brome.
Full of gladness; joyful; glad. [R.] -- Glad"ful*ness, n. [R.]Spenser.It followed him with gladful glee. Spenser.
A nitrogenous substance, C8H7NO, isomeric with oxindol,obtained as an oily liquid.
Nihility; nothingness. [R.]
To growl; to snarl.And wolves are gnarling who shall gnaw thee first. Shak.
Same as Angiospermous.
A work of art or of human industry, of an early epoch;especially, a book printed before A. D. 1500.
Obsequiousness; obedience. [Obs.] Evelyn.
Peerless; incomparable. [Obs.] Spenser.
To bear sway over.
To follow closely, or so as to overtake; to pursue. [Obs.]To follow and detain him, if by any possibility he could besubsecuted and overtaken. E. Hall.
A variety of bacterium; a microscopic, rod-shaped vegetableorganism.
The state of being ethereal; etherealness.Something of that ethereality of thought and manner which belonged toWordsworth's earlier lyrics. J. C. Shairp.
One who rejoices.
A sigh or sobbing; also, a hiccough. [Obs.] Spenser. W. Browne.
See Melanotype.
Made by complete closure of the mouth organs; shut; -- said ofcertain consonants (p, b, t, d, etc.). H. Sweet.
Passing to the west.Toward heaven's descent had sloped his westering wheel. Milton.
A native of China; a Chinese.
The fold of skin which covers the glans of the penis; theprepuce.
An instrument for cutting into the fetal head, to facilitatedelivery.
One who overlooks.
Methyl alcohol, CH3OH; -- also, by extension, any one in thehomologous series of paraffine alcohols of which methyl alcohol isthe type.

Openly declared, avowed, acknowledged, or claimed; as, aprofessed foe; a professed tyrant; a professed Christian. Theprofessed (R. C. Ch.) , a certain class among the Jesuits bound by aspecial vow. See the note under Jesuit.
A red nose. Shak.
Esoteric doctrine or principles.
Belonging to the Aplacentata; without placenta.
An oath.
Crystallized litharge, obtained by fusion in the form of fineyellow scales.
One of the followers of Lucifer, bishop of Cagliari, in thefourth century, who separated from the orthodox churches because theywould not go as far as he did in opposing the Arians.
A commercial name for green aniline dye.
Producing reeds or canes.
To a very great degree; beyond what is usual; surpassingly. Itsignifies more than very.
In a stagnant manner.
To divest of the office or authority of a magistrate. [Obs.]Milton.

The part of a ship which is ordinarily under water; hence, thevessel itself; a ship.My ventures are not in one bottom trusted. Shak.Not to sell the teas, but to return them to London in the samebottoms in which they were shipped. Bancroft.Full bottom, a hull of such shape as permits carrying a large amountof merchandise.
Without a carpet.
Admitting of being compared; like. [Obs.] Gower.
The reed bunting. It has a collar of white feathers. Calledalso ring bunting.
Excessively greedy.
Moving with a bound or bounds.The bounding pulse, the languid limb. Montgomery.
The act of ascertaining; a reducing to certainty; a finding outby investigation; discovery.The positive ascertainment of its limits. Burke.
The state of being devoted, or set apart by a vow. [R.] Bp.Hurd.
A method of taking photographic pictures, on paper sensitizedwith iodide of silver; -- also called Talbotype, from the inventor,Mr. Fox. Talbot.
Two pieces of bread and butter with a thin slice of meat,cheese, or the like, between them.

The chips or fragments made by boring. Boring bar, a revolvingor stationary bar, carrying one or more cutting tools for dressinground holes.-- Boring tool (Metal Working), a cutting tool placed in a cutterhead to dress round holes. Knight.
The quality or state of being imperious; arrogance;haughtiness.Imperiousness and severity is but an ill way of treating men who havereason of their own to guide them. Locke.
Same as Hæmatoplastic.

In Ireland, a lord or proprietor of a tract of land or of acastle, elected by a family, under the system of tanistry.This family [the O'Hanlons] were tanists of a large territory withinthe present county of Armagh. M. A. Lower.
The platform about the head of the mainmast in square-riggedvessels.

To make numb; to deprive of the power of sensation or motion;to render senseless or inert; to deaden; to benumb; to stupefy.For lazy winter numbs the laboring hand. Dryden.Like dull narcotics, numbing pain. Tennyson.
A division of dipterous insects in which the proboscis is largeand contains lancelike mandibles and maxillæ. The horseflies androbber flies are examples.
An earnest; earnest money; money paid to bind a bargain.[Scot.] Arles penny, earnest money given to servants. Kersey.
The act, process or method of determining the amount and kindof sugar present in sirup, molasses, and the like, especially by theemployment of polarizing apparatus.

An instrument for recording, preserving, and reproducingsounds, the record being a tracing of a phonautograph etched in somesolid material. Reproduction  is accomplished by means of a systemattached to an elastic diaphragm.
Muddy; slimy; thick. Sir T. Browne.
Swallowing up. Wodhull.
The word is used as a Portuguese designation of money ofaccount, one hundred reis being about equal in value to eleven cents.
An instrument or apparatus in which water is separated byevaporation or distillation; the part of a distilling apparatus inwhich the separation of the vapors is effected.
The light elastic wood of the Aspidosperma excelsum, a tree ofGuiana having a fluted trunk readily split into planks.
To call by a wrong title.
Capability of being persuaded. Hawthorne.
The business of making or managing rafts.
Having the pistil come to maturity before the stamens;protogynous; -- opposed to proterandrous.
Having many faces.
Made or contrived for getting small sums of money from theignorant or unwary; as, a catchpenny book; a catchpenny show.-- n.
A country seat; a country or suburban residence of somepretensions to elegance. Dryden. Cowper.
One who uses, or is skilled in the use of, an oar; a rower.

The act of doing what magnificent; the state or quality ofbeing magnificent. Acts xix. 27. "Then cometh magnificence." Chaucer.And, for the heaven's wide circuit, let it speak The Maker's highmagnificence, who built so spacious. Milton.The noblest monuments of Roman magnificence. Eustace.
A rounded mass of cloud, with shining white edges; a cumulus, -- often appearing before a thunderstorm.
Suitableness; agreement. [Obs.] hak.
A genus of leguminous herbs with densely spiked flowers andusually trifoliate leaves; trefoil. There are many species, all ofwhich are called clover. See Clover.
To make glib. [Obs.] Bp. Hall.
Hastily; immediately; instantly; on the spot; hotfloot. Gower.Custance have they taken anon, foothot. Chaucer.
An orphan. [Obs.] Udcll.
A transparent or translucent variety of common feldspar, ororthoclase, which often shows pearly opalescent reflections; --called by lapidaries moonstone.
A convulsive tic similar to or identical with miryachit,observed among the woodsmen of Maine.
Having an air or manner characteristic of the stage;theatrical; artificial; as, a stagy tone or bearing; --chiefly useddepreciatively.
A petty politician; a pretender in politics. Milton.
One who utters a shriek.

Primarily, liberty of converse; intercourse; hence, acertificate, given after compliance with quarantine regulations,permitting a ship to land passengers and crew; -- a term usedparticularly in the south of Europe.
To hie. [Obs.]Men must high them apace, and make haste. Holland.
With pusillanimity.
A man whose occupation is to make malt.
One of the States of the United States of America.-- a.
Liable to be lost. [R.]
A periodical work published once a quarter, or four times in ayear.
Same as Tromp.
One who believes in incorporealism. Cudworth.
A sea god in the service of Neptune who assumed differentshapes at will. Hence, one who easily changes his appearance orprinciples.
Efficacious against syphilis.-- n.
Relating to, or having the properties of, a caustic curveformed by reflection. See Caustic, a. Nichol.
The act or process of retenting; the state of having relented.Sir T. Browne.
A short bar used by thieves to wrench doors open. [Written alsobettee.]The powerful betty, or the artful picklock. Arbuthnot.
A stranger. [Obs.] Spenser.
The quality or state of being prodigious; the state of havingqualities that excite wonder or astonishment; enormousness; vastness.
In an inscrutable manner.
To jumble together.
One who is fond of forest or forest scenery; a haunter of thewoods. [R.]
Having a good temper; not easily vexed. See Good-natured.
Random. [Obs.] Spenser.
In a clumsy manner.
To exclude from participation in; to excommunicate. [Obs.]Poets . . . were excommuned Plato's common wealth Gayton.
To bully. [Obs.]She shan't think to bullock and domineer over me. Foote.
Earlier form of Acknow. [Obs.] To be aknow, to acknowledge; toconfess. [Obs.]
Of or pertaining to the gyrostat or to gyrostatics.
Of or pertaining to the thigh or leg, or to any of the partscalled crura; as, the crural arteries; crural arch; crural canal;crural ring.
The first word of any page of a book after the first, insertedat the right hand bottom corner of the preceding page for theassistance of the reader. It is seldom used in modern printing.
Not having or making pretenses.
See Pasha.
To perish. [Obs.] Chaucer.
To make peculiar; to set appart or assign, as an exclusivepossession. [R.] Dr. John Smith.
Accumulation of air, or other gas, and of pus, in the pleuralcavity.
The room or place where players dress for the stage.
One versed in orchidology.
A semibreve. [R.]
Lubric.
Made friends; reconciled. [Obs.] "Deadly foes . . .affriended." Spenser.
The epithelial lining of the ventricles of the brain and thecanal of the spinal cord; endyma; ependymis.
To deliver up by one government to another, as a fugitive fromjustice. See Extradition.
The quality of being permissible; permissibleness;allowableness.
Being beyond, or exceeding, the power or laws of nature;miraculous.
Spreading widely.
To be overbusy or unduly anxious about trifles; to make abustle or ado. Sir W. Scott.
A smart, ready, and witty reply.Cupid was as bad as he; Hear but the youngster's repartee. Prior.
A sending out; emission. [Obs.] Sir T. Browne.
Angulous. [R.]
In a trusty manner.
One who annuls. [R.]
Erysipelatous.
In a reproving manner.
The original native name for the ancient Ethiopic language orpeople. See Ethiopic.
Having no mistrust or suspicion.The swain mistrustless of his smutted face. Goldsmith.
A building up; construction. [Obs.] Cockeram.
A blowing together, as of many instruments in a concert, or ofmany fires in a foundry. [R.]  Bacon.
A great brazen laver in the temple at Jerusalem; -- so calledfrom its size.He made a molten sea of ten cubits from brim to brim, round incompass, and five cubits the height thereof. 2 Chron. iv. 2.
An African genet (Genetta pardina). See Genet.
Standardized; determined or analyzed by titration; as, titratedsolutions.
A dry, cold, violent, northerly wind of the Adriatic.
After the manner of the Japanese; resembling japanned articles.Carlyle.
A young hog.
A joint cause. Fotherby.
Rejection by judicial sentence. [R.] Knowles.
The condition or state of being free from fever.
The glycerin salt of ricinoleic acid, occuring as acharacteristic constituent of castor oil; -- formerly called palmin.

Any device in which an imperfectly conducting contact betweenpieces of metal or other conductors loosely resting against eachother is materially improved in conductivity by the influence ofHertzian waves; -- so called by Sir O. J. Lodge in 1894 on theassumption that the impact of the electic waves caused the looselyconnected parts to cohere, or weld together, a condition easilydestroyed by tapping. A common form of coherer as used in wirelesstelegraphy consists of a tube containing filings (usually a pinch ofnickel and silver filings in equal parts) between terminal wires orplugs (called conductor plugs).
